    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.9.6-7_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">MRS. T.W. TODD
                        <lb/>
                    <unclear>455</unclear> RUTHVEN AVENUE
                        <lb/>
                    PALO ALTO, CALIFORNIA</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Jan 21, 1922</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I enclose the account of the fight with Father's signature. He suggested some <unclear>alterations</unclear> which you will note. Mr. Plily was sent out, he says in a different direction and with a different body of men, but deserves quite as much credit as Mr. Donovan, tho<sic>though</sic> the promise to return and sense of direction that made him so invaluable a guide, were Mr. Donovan's. I thought
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.9.6-7_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                    
                    you might be interested to hear a further statement he made of having met Mr. Pliley years afterward and that at that time he told him that his feet were too badly swollen by the cactus injuries to wear any kind of shoes, so he bought the largest carpet slippers he could find, slit them and then formed them on his feet!<del/></p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours</salute>
                
                    <signed>Helen M. Todd</signed> 
                </closer>
                
                <note type="Neihardt"><!--in another hand--> Daughter of Morton in <hi rend= "underline">Indian Wars</hi></note>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
